I soon discovered that it was impossible for him to live, and asked him what he thought of the chances for his recovery. He replied promptly "I can not live," "my wound is mortal,"! He then asked me if I thought there was any chance for him, I told him that the physicians thought it impossible for him to recover. When he found that I was a minister he seemed pleased and though very weak-- disposed to talk on the subject of religion. He said he had never belonged to any church-- had never made a profession of religion-- but had always had a high respect for the church, and for religion. I feared he would rely too much upon a moral and correct life which he had been careful to maintain, I discovered.


I gave him my views in refference to our good works, and the way of salvation through christ, & through him alone. He fully concurred, and seemed much engaged. I had charge of a boat with some "Five hundred" wounded on board-- others were in the same suffering and dying condition I saw him-- however every few minutes-- to give him water or what ever else he wanted-- He was always glad to see me and received me with a smile-- I went to him about midnight Tuesday night-- he was on the upper deck of the boat -- it was raining very hard-- it was full moon-- though cloudy yet not so dark but I could see him and he me distinctly. I sang Kirk White's hymn "The Star of Bethlehem" -- to the tune "Bonny Doon"


5

The hymn commences "When Marshalled on the nightly plain" &c When I came to the verse

"Once on the raging seas I rode;

The Storm was loud, the night was dark;

The ocean yawned, and rudely blowed the

The wind that tossed my foundering bark.

Deep horror then my vitals froze;

Death-struck, I ceased the tide to stem;

When suddenly a star arrose -- 

It was the Star of Bethlehem!"
